                            <comment id="17081732" author="jnioche" created="Sun, 12 Apr 2020 10:22:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;IMHO it would be preferable to make the outputCollector threadsafe - this is the case in 1.x and apart from solving the problem experienced in&#160; &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/STORM-3582&quot; title=&quot;Kryo errors when using custom serialization&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;STORM-3582&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;STORM-3582&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; , it would greatly simplify things. Having to change the user code to enforce synchronization would be a pain. As for eliminating multithreading inside a bolt, well, again this would be a regression compared to 1.x and simply not possible in some cases.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17126069" author="ethanli" created="Thu, 4 Jun 2020 16:46:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Not only outputCollector is not thread safe. There is a metricsTick that also uses ExecutorTransfer to transfer tuple.  In the case of single threaded bolt, all of outputcollector and metricsTick happen in one thread, which is fine. But if there are multiple threads in the bolt, ExecutorTransfer transfer can happen in different threads. There will be data corruption since the serializer is not thread safe.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
